Where is boasting then? It is excluded. By what law? Of works? No, but by the law of faith.
Therefore we conclude that a man is justified by faith without the deeds of the law.
<FI>Is He<Fi> the God of the Jews only? <FI>Is He<Fi> not also the God of the Gentiles? Yes, of the Gentiles also,
since there is one God who will justify the circumcised by faith and the uncircumcised through faith.
Do we then make void the law through faith? God forbid! On the contrary, we establish the law.
What then shall we say that Abraham our father has found according to the flesh?
Because, if Abraham was justified by works, he has <FI>something<Fi> to boast about, but not before God.
Because what does the Scripture say? “Abraham believed God, and it was accounted to him for righteousness.”
Now to him who works, the wages are not counted as grace but as debt.
